Subject: [PATCH] cmake/modules/AddSwift.cmake: fix host-tool cross-compile
 flag leakage and dead-strip gating when the build host is Darwin and the
 target SDK isn't

When cross-compiling Swift host tools to a non-Apple SDK (e.g. ANDROID)
from a Darwin (macOS) build machine, two of AddSwift.cmake's host-variant
helper functions behave incorrectly because they gate only on the build
host being Darwin, not on whether the actual target SDK is also an Apple
platform:

1. _add_host_variant_c_compile_link_flags: some per-target compile lines
   pick up a stray "-arch <host arch> -isysroot <host SDK>" pair from
   elsewhere in Swift's CMake macros (not pinned down to one exact source
   after tracing through the host-variant flag helpers and CMake's own
   Apple Silicon default-arch enforcement). clang rejects -arch outright
   for a non-Darwin -target triple, aborting the compile. Downgrading it
   to a silently-ignored unused argument via -Qunused-arguments, gated to
   only the cross-to-non-Apple-SDK case, covers every
   add_swift_host_library target without patching each one individually.

2. _add_host_variant_link_flags: the -dead_strip optimization is gated on
   `CMAKE_SYSTEM_NAME MATCHES Darwin` alone, which stays true even when
   cross-compiling to Android from this same Darwin machine. The
   Darwin-only linker flag "-Wl,-dead_strip" then reaches ld.lld, which
   doesn't recognize it as a valid ELF/Android linker argument. Require
   the actual host-variant SDK to be an Apple platform too.

Both fixes have an exact counterpart in
stdlib/cmake/modules/AddSwiftStdlib.cmake's
_add_target_variant_c_compile_link_flags /_add_target_variant_link_flags
(the add_swift_target_library side of the same issue; see that patch).

This patch is a candidate for filing upstream.

Sentinel: NUCLEUS_SWIFT_SOURCE_ANDROID_DARWIN_HOST_ADD_SWIFT_CMAKE

diff --git a/cmake/modules/AddSwift.cmake b/cmake/modules/AddSwift.cmake
index b52fe0d5c0c..c9c2de350f2 100644
--- a/cmake/modules/AddSwift.cmake
+++ b/cmake/modules/AddSwift.cmake
@@ -115,6 +115,23 @@ endfunction()
 # Usage:
 # _add_host_variant_c_compile_link_flags(name)
 function(_add_host_variant_c_compile_link_flags name)
+  if(CMAKE_HOST_SYSTEM_NAME STREQUAL "Darwin" AND
+     NOT "${SWIFT_HOST_VARIANT_SDK}" IN_LIST SWIFT_DARWIN_PLATFORMS)
+    # Cross-compiling to a non-Apple SDK (e.g. ANDROID) from a Darwin build
+    # machine: some of these per-target compile lines pick up a stray
+    # "-arch <host arch> -isysroot <host SDK>" pair from somewhere in
+    # Swift's CMake macros that we were unable to pin down exactly. clang
+    # then rejects -arch outright as unsupported for the non-Darwin
+    # -target triple actually being compiled for. Downgrading it to a
+    # silently-ignored unused argument here, once, covers every
+    # add_swift_host_library target. See the matching guard in
+    # stdlib/cmake/modules/AddSwiftStdlib.cmake's
+    # _add_target_variant_c_compile_link_flags for the add_swift_target_library
+    # counterpart of this same issue.
+    target_compile_options(${name} PRIVATE
+      $<$<COMPILE_LANGUAGE:C,CXX,OBJC,OBJCXX>:-Qunused-arguments>)
+  endif()
+
   # MSVC and gcc don't understand -target.
   # clang-cl understands --target.
   if(CMAKE_C_COMPILER_ID MATCHES "Clang")
@@ -430,7 +447,15 @@ function(_add_host_variant_link_flags target)
   #
   # TODO: Evaluate/enable -f{function,data}-sections --gc-sections for bfd,
   # gold, and lld.
-  if(NOT CMAKE_BUILD_TYPE STREQUAL "Debug" AND CMAKE_SYSTEM_NAME MATCHES Darwin)
+  # CMAKE_SYSTEM_NAME MATCHES Darwin alone isn't a reliable guard when
+  # cross-compiling to a non-Apple SDK (e.g. ANDROID) from a Darwin build
+  # machine — see the matching comment in
+  # stdlib/cmake/modules/AddSwiftStdlib.cmake's
+  # _add_target_variant_link_flags for the add_swift_target_library
+  # counterpart of this same issue. Require the actual host-variant SDK to
+  # be Apple too.
+  if(NOT CMAKE_BUILD_TYPE STREQUAL "Debug" AND CMAKE_SYSTEM_NAME MATCHES Darwin
+     AND "${SWIFT_HOST_VARIANT_SDK}" IN_LIST SWIFT_DARWIN_PLATFORMS)
     if (NOT SWIFT_DISABLE_DEAD_STRIPPING)
       # See rdar://48283130: This gives 6MB+ size reductions for swift and
       # SourceKitService, and much larger size reductions for sil-opt etc.
